The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     SPORT BRIEFS
                                                    
	Kalmadi   re-elected IOA president  Pune: Suresh Kalmadi was on Friday re-elected the Indian Olympic Association (IOA) president for the fourth successive term in a row at the elections of the apex national sports body. He won the post uncontested.   V. K. Malhotra has been elected senior vice-president, while Randhir Singh and A. K. Mattoo has been re-elected as general secretary and treasurer respectively.     
	 Tim sentence  Washington: Banned US track star Tim Montgomery, was on Friday sentenced to five years in prison on heroin charges.  Montgomery, was sentenced in federal court in Norfolk, Virginia for conspiracy to possess with the intent to distribute more than 100 grams of heroin, according to a court document.     
	 EB search  Calcutta: The East Bengal club will request the All India Football Federation (AIFF) to seek a replacement for Edmilson Marques, who is down with jaundice, says A Staff Reporter. Speculations are rife that the club is looking for former Dempo and Sporting Club striker Dudu Omagbemi.     
	 T20 tie on  London: A series of transatlantic phone calls between the billionaires at the head of two warring factions was necessary to ensure that England rsquo;s winner-take-all $20m Twenty20 match in Antigua on November 1 will go ahead as planned.    
	 Stallions join  Calcutta: Pakistan captain Shoaib Malik will lead Sialkot Stallions in the Champions League Twenty20, says A Staff Reporter.   THE TEAMS: Rajasthan Royals and Chennai Super Kings (India), Western Australia Warriors and Victoria Bushrangers (Australia), Titans and Dolphins (South Africa), Sialkot Stallions (Pakistan) and Middlesex (England)     
	 Lara rsquo;s wishes  Mumbai: Brian Lara on Thursday offered Sachin Tendulkar his best wishes for breaking his world record of scoring the most number of runs in Tests, but said he would not be present personally to hail the milestone if and when it happens.    
	 Jaffer captain  Mumbai: Wasim Jaffer was on Friday named captain of the Mumbai team for the upcoming Ranji Trophy.     
	 IPL payment  Colombo: The Indian Premier League (IPL) will pay $40 million to the cash-strapped Sri Lanka Cricket (SLC) as guarantee money the SLC will forfeit due to cancellation of the two-Test series in England next year. 
                                                                                                                                                               
